First of all, please be aware that they WILL try to upsell you on things you don‚Äôt need. I was told that I needed an antibiotic treatment due to an gum infection in my mouth.  I was pretty shocked by this because I have good oral hygiene- but of course when a professional tells you something like that the first reaction is to trust them. However- in retrospect it really did not make any sense. They gave me a small tray of foam to put on my teeth and I held it there for 30 seconds or so and took it out. If I really had an infection that would not have really helped, it was just a way they could get an additional $50 out of me. At the end of my appointment, which other than the upselling was fairly standard, they told me I should see a gum specialist due to gum recession and said they had a great doctor in house, Dr. Pedram Fakheri.
My second appointment at Beverly Hills Prestige Dental Group with Dr. Pedram Fekhari is when things got even worse. After inviting me into my dental chair fairly quickly after my arrival, they kept me sitting there for 45 minutes. Normally I would be understanding o this- however there is NO PARKING at Beverly Hills Prestige Dental Group. So you have to search all over the area for street parking and the best I could find was 2 hour metered parking.  So if your appointment is long and they have you waiting for a long time the meter will expire and you will get a parking ticket.
I finally went back to the front desk to see what was going on and right then they said he could see me. On first meeting him he began peppering me with condescending and rude trick questions. For example ‚Äúwhat are you doing here‚Äù, ‚Äúis gum recessing bad‚Äù, ‚Äúif something does hurt it means t‚Äôs not bad for you, right?‚Äù. Then he proceeded to pull up google images on the computer to show me examples of gums- strange since I can and did do that at home before the appointment. Lastly, he only looked at my mouth for about 20 seconds to identify which gums were receding and told me a needed a gum graft surgery. At this point I was feeling very uneasy and skeptical that he would suggest such a drastic surgery without even measuring the depth of my gum pockets or even closely evaluating teeth for longer than a couple seconds. He went on to say I need to decide whether I wanted to use cadaver tissue or my won for the surgery, making sure to say using cadaver tissue would make his life easier. I was chocked and creeped out to have this conversation about 5 minutes of meeting him. I told him I need to think about it more before committing (really just trying to escape and get out of there) and he told me that ‚Äúyeah you need to do more research‚Äù.

Overall I cannot recommend this office and particular do not recommend Dr. Pedram Fakheri. They will upsell you, try and get you to do things you do not need, and will condescending you in the process.

< review>
Better late than never. I had a regular cleaning scheduled in January. I chose Dr. Javdan based on the reviews I saw here, which are largely positive. My appointment started with 14 xrays. Never in my life have I had so many xrays done at the dentist. They said 18 is for the full mouth, but they only did 14, which is pretty standard procedure. My standard is 4 xrays, not 14. I assume it‚Äôs a result of dated equipment.

I then met with the hygienist, who is super sweet, gentle and very educational. She explained in a lot of detail what is happening and why. This was great, but there was also a lot of repeated information and it took a lot of time. As most hygenists do, she explained the proper flossing technique, which involved going up and down 5 times along the tooth on each side of the gums.

She recommended a deep cleaning, which I was on the fence about due to cost and the amount of time it‚Äôd take. They gave me a cost break down, which was nice. They said the basic cleaning involves an antibacterial treatment, which is $95 out of pocket. I asked if I could have the cleaning without the antibacterial treatment and they said no because it was somehow incorporated into the rest of the cleaning. I chose to go with the basic cleaning and told them I‚Äôd think about doing a deep cleaning when I have more time since the appointment had already been well over an hour long. So they proceed to do the cleaning. Turns out the antibacterial treatment is entirely separate and could easily be removed from the cleaning.

The hygienist who taught me the proper flossing technique hardly even flossed my teeth. The floss went in and out, not even rubbing the teeth on either side once, let alone 5 times. It‚Äôs the fastest cleaning I‚Äôve ever had. Probably took 1-2 min total for the brushing and flossing combined. Then the dentist came in for 30 seconds‚Äîopened my mouth, looked in, said it looks fine and asked as he was walking out the door if I had considered braces to which I responded that I‚Äôd had them and that they messed up my jaw. The latter part of my response about my jaw should have sparked some questions, but that was it. Appointment was done, so I walked out.

I scheduled another appointment and asked for an 8am appointment whenever there was one available. The receptionist scrutinized my request asking why I need 8 am and such rather than simply giving me the dates where 8am was available as I had already told her I was flexible with the date. They also do not validate for parking. Paid an extra $17 for parking since the appointment took 2+ hours. 2+ hours for a subpar cleaning. Definitely have no plans on going back.< /review>

<text>WORST DENTIST EXPERIENCE I'VE EVER HAD

The first time I went to Dr. Javdan was for a chipped tooth. He filled in my tooth but I could still feel that it was not bonded smoothly. I told him it didn't feel right and he dismissed me responding, "I don't see anything," without even looking at my tooth with the overhead light. I left feeling he was rushing to be done with me and was unbothered with my uneasiness about his work.

4 months later I notice there's brown spots on the tooth Dr. Javdan bonded. Not only did he not smooth my tooth properly, he also left air bubbles on the tooth that turned brown.

So I returned to him so he could correct his work.
Dr. Javdan was very rough when he started to repair my tooth. He was gripping my top lip with so much force it went numb and caused my lip to swell. He finished and I could clearly see he had not buffed the whole tooth, he just buffed in one spot. This made the tooth have an obvious spot polish look in one spot on the tooth and not on the whole tooth. I told him that it didn't look good and once again he responded, "I don't see what you're talking about." I told him it wasn't right and had to really insist. Annoyed he said, "Do you want me to put more bonding on?"  Why is he asking me instead of repairing the tooth in whatever capacity that he sees as fit to get the desired look???  Unprofessional.

I told him that he forcefully held my lip and now the left side of my top lip was swollen. He responded, "what happened to your lip?" and I said before you started working my lip was fine. He kept saying I must be allergic to latex. I told him I was not allergic and that he used unnecessary force. Yet he NEVER apologized, just claimed I was allergic and was really unsympathetic about the situation.

At this point there was no way I could sit back down in his chair when he was so blatantly unconcerned about my comfort and/or dental well being. When he left the room I went to speak to the manager, Aracely.

I showed her my lip and tooth and she agreed that both were not good. However, she kept insisting I let him fix it. I told her that I did not want to be in the room alone with him and that I was uncomfortable.

Dr. Javdan over hears us talking and starts insisting that I let him continue working on my tooth. I said, "No, I'm done." He responds, "just come and I will fix!" and he comes over to me and starts repeating, "just come and I will fix," at this point I have told him NO a few times. Instead of him giving me space and accepting that he has lost a client, he comes over to me and invades my personal space...

He's STILL insisting I let him finish fixing my tooth and I turn to him and say NO firmly. He CONTINUES to try to pressure me to come back to his chair. To get away from him I walk out of the office side and into the waiting room side, in an attempt to remove him from my personal space. He sees that I'm past annoyed with him yet Dr. Javdan then follows me into the waiting room. Saying, "I want to see if you're allergic to latex." I shout "LEAVE ME ALONE!" and he laughs sarcastically and goes back into the office side.

At this point I'm so upset that I'm crying. I ask the manager Aracely did she know of any other dentist that she could refer me to - of course she didn't know of anyone else.

The experience I had with Dr. Javdan at Beverly Prestige Dental was more than disappointing and unprofessional - it was devastating. I left the office in tears with a half buffed tooth and swollen lip.  The absolute worst.</text>< Pictures>

< review>
In my experiences with other Dentist in LA I never felt like my dental health was actually being taken in to concern until I found Dr Javdan.  The entire process of getting two crowns put on my teeth was both incredibly thorough and painless.

The wonderful women at the front desk were so pleasant to deal with and took the time necessary to explain to me my dental benefits from my insurance so that there were no surprises which I really appreciated considering how difficult understanding insurance and treatments can be.

I really felt like Dr. Javdan went above and beyond to make me feel comfortable and informed about the procedures he was doing and how he was doing them.  I was consistently asked if I was experiencing any pain so that it could be managed but that was never the case.

Most of all I felt like Dr. Javdan cared more about making sure my teeth were healthy then trying to do a bunch of unnecessary things to make more money which was my experience previously in LA.  When my insurance ran out and I needed an additional consultation with an Endodontist he saw the concern in my face knowing that I had just spent all I could to get my teeth fixed already he arranged for the consultation in his office with  Dr. Mansouri who treated me as just as kind and caring as Dr. Javdan did.

I am moving to Colorado now and having finally found and incredible dentist here in LA I feel like its important to write a review like this for all the people out there like myself who were searching for the right fit but didn't know where to look.  Thanks again Dr. Javdan and Dr. Mansouri you make all the difference in the world with you talent and generosity.  I would give me recommendation Dr. Javdan at the highest level.< /review>

< Text>
I said once before that I would never take my car for an oil change at Jiffy Lube from a previous horrendous experience and a ruined car. After nearly 20 years nothing has changed. Due to Covid19 I was needing a oil change and decided to take my Lincoln in for a oil change and that seemed to work out well at first (this is what I thought, will come back to this car later) so I decided to bring my Saturn in for the same thing, before they started I explain if they are not familiar with the process for this car then I will tell you that this drain plug must have a seal and if it's not installed correctly then it will leak also that their is baffles in the valve cover that only allows you to pour oil in slowly. This information was not heard, they acted as if they already knew. This was as far from the truth, when the work was done I left but moments later I smelled burning oil and pulled over, opened the hood and found oil all over the engine and that oil poured right on top of the catalytic converter and was smoldering ( this is how Jiffy Lube ruined my other Saturn caught on fire) so I returned and they attempted to clean of the oil with water and air, this did nothing, I returned home to find oil leaking from the plug that I explained About the seal. With My previous Saturn I returned and their fix was to keep tightening the plug untill they stripped oil pan and the plug, (oil pan and plug had to be replaced at the dealership) so the seal is there for a reason. Now the remody was to have a second and third opinion for the work was not performed correctly and also found no torque wrench was used to set the specs on the plug. I filed a compliant with the BBB and Bureau of Automotive Repair over the work and to make matters worse, remember the Lincoln I took in the beginning of this issue? Well it turns out on inspection of that work, the oil was changed but not the filter, the dirty, filthy, old filter that was on the car since the last change (by Firestone auto service) was still on the car, so that makes 2 cars with problems now after going back to Jiffy Lube. Never Never Again. Once this is inspected by the state so this can be documented. I will never return to any Jiffy Lube. I guess If your not a car person, then what you don't know won't hurt you, but it may cost you a lot of extra money and Time. It's just not worth it.</Text>

The Lambs feet were delicious, but understand when ordering it that it's the foot, so there isn't a lot of meat. But all that collagen makes the broth healing. The meat pie was delicious, too. Can't wait to try more from here. The house made yogurt is a must.</review>< Gmap_id>
0x80c2dab44131a9bb:0x70d9bd3b5269d592< /Gmap_id>
</record></dataset><record>
<userid>118406615368414521572<//userid><user_name>John Wie< /user_name><Time>1618185461360<//Time><rate>5</rate>< Text>
Omar Restaurant is a great Xinjiang stop that is delicious and unique.

Currently during the pandemic (as of 4/10/21), indoor dining is not available and they unfortunately don't have an area set-up for outdoor dining. They do have a big parking area available and you'll be ordering through their backdoor entrance. At 2:00PMish on a Saturday, things were quiet (my friend and I were the only customers). We were greeted by the owner, who cooked our food in about 15 minutes. I forget if they were cash only but would advise to definitely have cash on hand just in case.

We both got the lag man (the hand-pulled noodles). There were plenty of noodles and was absolutely delicious. It comes with a big container of the spicy oil, lamb, and veggies (would advise that for two people, should probably get either a second order or another entree on the side). Even taking the food from the SGV back home to the OC, and slightly reheating the items, it was still super delicious. The spice isn't too hot (about a light medium) and it definitely filled me up!

Definitely would suggest to stop by if you love noodles, lamb, and more! I asked the owner's son how business was and he said that things were fairly so-so and haven't changed much since the start of the pandemic, so if you've been a fan in the past or think you want to give it a try, definitely support Omar's Halal Restaurant!</Text>

<text>I liked lag-man and hot&salty milk tea! Lag-man can be better if made a little bit thinner, but in general it was very good! As I used to eat in Kazakhstan.
Lamb kebab was very small, I would say tiny  4 skewers were not enough for 1 lady with small volume of stomach.
We would definitely come back because of lag-man, but would not order kebabs any more. Would like to try Big plate chicken with noodle and meat pie on our next visit!
Parking space for few autos is available to customers for free.
Only few tables are inside - this place looks like someone's home from Asia, but it is cosy and authentic. I felt myself like I am a guest here.
Waiter is not really fluent in english, but she got the idea of what we would like to get. Also we had a chance to see how our dishes were prepared by the chef. Now I want to learn how to pull lag-man by myself.
P.S. pay attention that this place is not working from 3pm till 5pm each day and on Tuesday!<//text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOH5m1y-C3yY794OGTf25p45_GLDlnL4HU30Jam=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPC7B76udYg0RIZ74f5kYby8dfLbpqjZBlPB14x=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><Resp>None< /Resp><GmapID>0x80c2dab44131a9bb:0x70d9bd3b5269d592< /GmapID></record>

< text>
A real family-run restaurant (very impressed with the young son multitasking like a professional host/ server).  I had my first Uyghur meal ever, and enjoyed the lamb skewers, the hand drawn noodles, the soup (I believe there is only one on the menu; it was great), and of course the much praised big chicken dish. The yoghurt was sweet and tasty. The salty milk tea something to have experienced once.  Quite A display of regional art/ craft,  but don't come for high class (the restaurant ran out of chairs when we were there with a group of 10).  No alcohol served. Great experience.<//text>

<Date>1550241032321</Date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
< review>
We had lamb flat cake, lamb clear soup with noodles, tofu, and big plate chicken noodles.

Pros:
+ Halal Xinjiang food, not too common in that area
+ Colorful decor
+ You can hear grandma making noodles in the kitchen. Noodles had nice chewiness to them. Good sauce, lots of depth

Cons:
- a bit crowded
- Their service is kind of an acquired taste. It didn't bother me but some people in our party said they wouldn't come again b/c of the service. I thought it was fine - it's not "professional," but it reminded me of when you go over to your aunt's to visit and she forces your kid nephew to help serve you dinner and he would rather be playing video games and doesn't really want to see you anyway. If you think of it that way, you start finding it funny and growing a bit fond of the experience.

Overall, would come again for noodles.</review>

<gmap_id>0x80c2dab44131a9bb:0x70d9bd3b5269d592</gmap_id><review>Came here because Bon Appetit mentioned them in a recent article and since I wss in the area...This is a small restaurant located on the main street (4 lanes) in the area.  The food and the service is unpretentious - come in, order, and eat.  No ceremony, no discussion of The Vision.

The spicy ox tripe is tender but not that spicy (I think they didn't believe when I said make it hot), mixed with cilantro for a nice contrast to the tender, chewy tripe.

The cumin lamb was chopped and thoroughly cooked - probably more than it needed.

The naan is not the Indian naan you are probably familiar with.  This is more of a dry biscuit.  But that's good because it's perfect for absorbing the meat juices and oils from the cumin lamb.

Nothing earth-shatteringly exotic here, but still a good, filling meal.</review>< Time>

< date>
1521459557901</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
The significant other and I used to live in China. Our city had this great Xinjiang restaurant we would visit frequently and it's one of, if not the, biggest thing we miss about China.

We've tried to make their signature dish, the Da Pan Ji, or Big Plate Chicken, a few times at home. Omar Restaurant completely blows our attempts out of the water. It's everything we remember Da Pan Ji to be. We completely devoured it between the two of us. You MUST order a side of naan to soak up that  delicious sauce.

We also ordered the lamb kebabs and a lamb pie. Disclaimer - I'm not the biggest fan of lamb to begin with so I was pretty lukewarm about it. The S.O. enjoyed them though.

I would probably move back to the SGV area in a heartbeat just to be close to this restaurant and its Da Pan Ji.</review>

<text>Great place for different kind of Chinese food from UYGHUR muslim family with all halal meat (slaughtered muslim way). They make their own noodles, fresh. Don't expect fried rice or orange/kung pao kind of  Chinese dishes. They mostly serve lamb and chicken dishes. Meat pie(ground lamb) is a must try., Cumin lamb in skewers is awesome.. Big plate chicken is my favorite. I also tried the Spicy lamb feet (just a little too greasy for me) but minus the grease...it tasted great. It's family restaurant. I advive to go for lunch or early dinner as they run of "menu items" most of the time towards the end of the day. I take as positive. This means my food is fresh, not prepped days ago. Main dishes run between $15-$24.  Service is ok-- little kid helps mom after school. It is a 5/6 tables small CASH ONLY restaurant. One of my favorite eateries.<//text>< pics>

1458936800489<//Date>
<rate>4<//rate>< text>
Delicious specialized XinJiang Mom and pop shop. Western Northern China style, lamb galore. Kinda like Mongolian type of food. Not really any veggie dishes.

Specialized means it'll be appreciated by folks that love lamb, and xinjiang food.

Boiled lamb, xinjiang style $16.99 is a must for lamb lovers that love simple dishes. Young lamb meat.

Meat pie $13.99 super crispy is probably a general public must get.

Lag Man (hand-pulled noodles) $13.99.   Oily but the taste mixes well.

Pricey for 3 ppl but worth it if you're looking for their specific dishes, or yummy lamb dishes.< /text>

['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMUc93ZUw56VSR2Rbc1YLWUgnZ-DejWSfeAmWei=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><review>B Patisserie was an instant, addictive hit when it first opened several years ago. I simply couldn't resist chef Belinda Leong's elevated takes on viennoiserie and pastries, particularly the kouign amanns which were out of this world.

I hadn't visited for quite some time, so when I saw that Belinda had come up with special offerings just for Chinese New Year, I knew I had to try them before they were gone. The items I tried, whether the matcha tiramisu, the black sesame kouign amann, or the tiger sugar tapioca pudding, were very much in line with B Patisserie's regular, everyday offerings, only with Asian flavors that, in general, tend to be more subtle and less overpoweringly sweet than traditional Western sweets and pastries.

The matcha tiramisu, for example, had just enough green tea flavor in it, but not so much as to feel artificial or overwhelming. Same went for the tiger sugar tapioca pudding and even the black sesame kouign amann, although in the latter case it felt quite a bit smaller than the kouign amanns I'd enjoyed when B Patisserie first opened.

In any case, this is still world-class stuff, as Belinda's James Beard award attests. Despite her celebrity and success (a budding empire evidenced not only by B Patisserie's expanded store footprint but also by new ventures like B on the Go and Routier), you can still paparazzi her while she's hard at work in the open prep area, just behind the display cases. Keep up the great work, especially in representing the Bay Area's food scene on a national and even global scale, Belinda!</review><response>None< /response>< userid>

< review>
This bakery makes delicious pastries. One pastry I tasted a couple of months ago I loved. They only make this on weekends. However I've gone back three times since and this pastry is always sold out. Today I was at the bakery at 11:30 a.m. and they were out again. < text>
We had to wait for about 15 minutes on a Sunday morning, but definitely worth it! However, if you know what you want, there is an expedited order online and pick-up option. Chocolate kouign aman was very flaky with drippy chocolate, so not the right choice if you're wearing something fancy or trying to eat in a dignified manner, but it was so tasty!!! Chocolate croissant had an almost coffecake-like topping--not the traditional pain au chocolate, but definitely a pleasure. Coffee service was quick and drinks were delicious; I appreciated that there are oat milk lattes. Staff did a fantastic job managing flow safely to ensure social distancing, and they were also very friendly.</text>

< name>
Cami Griffiths<//name>
< date>
1620840711449<//date>
<userid>104440412157462190193< /userid><rate>5< /rate><Resp>None<//Resp>< Review>
My husband and I went here during our vacation and totally loved it! The bakery is welcoming and although Covid has changed things and you generally have to wait outside for your turn, the line went quickly and each employee was kind, welcoming and helpful. I was very impressed by each employee and the efficient and calm matter that they seemed to work in.
For our first time we got the Kouign Amann, the ginger molasses cookie and a hazelnut chocolate cake. The hazelnut chocolate cake left a little to be desired for me, the balance of flavors felt off but not a bad cake, just didn't stand out. On the other hand, my husband LOVED the Kouign Amann, it was wonderfully flakey and fresh, I was able to snatch a bite or two and agree that it was amazing. The ginger molasses cookie was my favorite and frankly, perfectly done, in my opinion. It was soft and chewy in the center, lightly crispy on the outside, had a beautiful light crunch from the sugar crystals and a fantastic balance of ginger and sweetness. I love ginger cookies but rarely are they done as well as the ones I got at b. Patisserie. We went back the very next day, ordered the Kouign Amann and Ginger cookie again and both were just as well done as the day before. I also ordered an almond banana chocolate crossiant for my mom which I gave her two days later when we went to visit, I had a bite myself and it tasted delicious! I can only imagine how good it must have tasted fresh! Lovely bakery, 5 stars without question, we hope to come again in the future.</Review>

<user_id>116407045966949106272< /user_id><user_name>Alison Jones< /user_name>< Time>
1585397750539<//Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate><text>If you want to taste some of the best desserts and vienoisserie the Bay Area has to offer.

With your "squad" for a foodie photoshoot for the  'gram...this isn't the kind of venue for all that nonsense. People here like to eat, not play with their food. If you MUST, get your order to go, then do your business OUTSIDE. There's better lighting anyway LOL!!!

B Patisserie is the best of the best in the Bay Area and always a must when I return to my other home away from home (Napa Valley)
On our most recent visit, we had our usual favorites- Chocolate and Classic Kougin Amann,  Passionfruit Bostock, and  Chocolate Chip Cookie. Another must is Chef Belinda Leong's desserts. This time,  we had the Chocolate Cream Cheese Budino, Black Sesame,  and Pumpkin Cheesecake. Always delicious, always consistent.

Another great thing to see is Chef Leong actually working alongside her pastry cooks, which was the case in every one of our visits in the past. VERY respectable,  considering you  rarely see the actual owner hustling with their staff on a  daily basis nowadays. You know what they say..."Teamwork makes the dream work!" She most definitely has a solid team behind her, and it shows.

It's always just been coffee and sweets for us, until we saw the table next to us enjoying the Ham and Cheese Tartine, so of course,  we had to try it(and it was BOMB!!!)and now it has become part of our hit list on every future visit to our favorite Patisserie in San Francisco.  ALOHA!!!

best desserts and vienoisserie the Bay Area has to offer.

With your "squad" for a foodie photoshoot for the  'gram...this isn't the kind of venue for all that nonsense. People here like to eat, not play with their food. If you MUST, get your order to go, then do your business OUTSIDE. There's better lighting anyway LOL!!!

B Patisserie is the best of the best in the Bay Area and always a must when I return to my other home away from home (Napa Valley)
On our most recent visit, we had our usual favorites- Chocolate and Classic Kougin Amann,  Passionfruit Bostock, and  Chocolate Chip Cookie. Another must is Chef Belinda Leong's desserts. This time,  we had the Chocolate Cream Cheese Budino, Black Sesame,  and Pumpkin Cheesecake. Always delicious, always consistent.

Another great thing to see is Chef Leong actually working alongside her pastry cooks, which was the case in every one of our visits in the past. VERY respectable,  considering you  rarely see the actual owner hustling with their staff on a  daily basis nowadays. You know what they say..."Teamwork makes the dream work!" She most definitely has a solid team behind her, and it shows.

It's always just been coffee and sweets for us, until we saw the table next to us enjoying the Ham and Cheese Tartine, so of course,  we had to try it(and it was BOMB!!!)and now it has become part of our hit list on every future visit to our favorite Patisserie in San Francisco.  ALOHA!!!

< text>
Absolutely the best bakery in the city, can't beat this 2018 James Beard award winner!  So many varieties of goods, everything is immaculately delicious.  Cakes are refined and complex in technique, exquisite taste. Croissants are buttery, flaky and slightly crunchy on the outside. Everything is wonderful here; the line moves quickly because they are well staffed.<//text>

< review>
This place is crazy busy prior to the pandemic with lots of options for pastries and cakes.  Since the shelter in place, they have reduced their menu as it is take away only.  Even with the small selection, the pastries are still very satisfying.  I do suggest getting a cookie for later.  Service here is friendly and they have some options for  "takeaways" which a small packages of treats.  My favorite of these are the Kouign Amann Ends.<//review>

You can't go wrong with the kouign amann. This is the place to go in SF for that pastry. They will have one of the original and then one unique flavor, so you can always try new flavors whenever you come. I haven't tried the other pastries. < review>
What a treat!  We swung by this bakery on our way to the Presidio, and boy did we luck out.  The line stretched out the door (around 11:15am) but moved quickly, and staff was simultaneously patient and helpful with recommendations.  We ended up getting a lunch sandwich each - I the mushroom and she the ham and cheese- I thought mine had a slight edge though the accompanying side salads were just as tasty.  We of course also got two Kouign-amanns, one regular and one chocolate, and a chocolate chip cookie that was warm and chewy.</review>

< userid>
112052219908680563744</userid>
<name>Joanna T< /name><date>1560779778341< /date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< Text>
Although there are many bakeries in San Francisco, few capture the quintessential experience of France that b patisserie achieves.
Here Belinda Leong, pastry chef extraordinaire and co-owner, works her magic. Laminated pastry dough is her medium.

The item she is most famous for is the kouign amann. The classic Breton pastry has layers of flaky pastry and caramelized sugar rolled into the shape of a Breton cap.
Leong makes the classic and an abundance of other flavors such as chocolate (to die for) and exotic flavors such as black sesame and passionfruit (my favorite).
Of course, other pastries shine here as well. There‚Äôs the banana chocolate croissant, the almond croissant, a stellar chocolate shard cookie. The baguette and the levain bread are both outstanding.

For ambiance, the cafe is chic reminiscent of Paris, mirrors on white walls through which you can admire the reflection of the baked goods or other patrons.

There is light fare for lunch. Sandwiches or salad. If you care for more on a slightly heavier scale, cross the street to B on the Go, her other casual dining cafe.

Outside the cafe is a parklet if you‚Äôd prefer to eat outdoors to take advantage of fine weather or sun.

When you come to b patisserie, imagine yourself in France enjoying fine food and decor. Relax. There is no more French-style cafe here in the City. Bon Appetit!< /Text>

<user>101604334147734489484< /user><username>Chris ‚ÄúVectrexer‚Äù Romero<//username>< time>

<Rating>2</Rating>< Text>
Came to b. Patisserie looking for a great French croissant in San Francisco.  While their croissant is not great, it is also not the worst ever. The is color, layering and finish. Bit all are a bit lacking except the color. For example, layering though extant, was a little poor and resulted in the product leaning towards a bread crescent rolls than a nice croissant. The crust, though browned, was soft instead of crisp. At $3.25 the value for the b. Patisserie croissant is middle low. I'd settle for in a pinch after drunken night out, but would head to one of my other places to get a French croissant made with artistry.

As for a direct comparison to actual French croissants experienced multiple times since 1992, b. Patisserie needs some work and some refresher training in a art of a perfect croissant.

Paired my croissant with a cappucino.  Decent cappucino but next time I am going to ask for more potency, and more heat.

The location is excellent and cut. A great place to relax for breakfast or lunch.  Large and clean windows to watch the world go by. Comfortable chairs and benches both inside, and caf√© style on the sidewalk to take in the sun.

Even though b. Patisserie is not my ideal croissant place I look forward to a return to enjoy some tarts and sandwiches sometime in the future.</Text>

< review>
The best Viennoiserie in San Francisco! The cafe is clean and modern and well staffed. The lines moved quickly and the were still many varieties available. The croissants are seasonally flavored (the chocolate banana so good), the kouign amann are the crown jewel (so flaky and light), the bostock are so soft yet creamy with almond paste.
Street parking, credit accepted, pleasant professional staff.<//review>

This is my favorite pastry store. However,  the quality was not as stable as before. I hope they can keep the quality at the same level. I drive at least 40 mins one way to buy the pastry. I got disappointed for couple of times.

I'm usually not a big pastry fan, but this place has me converted. We came here when traveling based off of a recommendation.

We tried the plum mixed berry kouigan-amann and the mixed berry almond croissant. They were both amazing and the best pastries I've ever had. The kouigan-amann was my favorite. I've never had anything like it! It was sweet, buttery, and delicious.

Service was fast‚Äîwe just picked out our pastries and paid at the counter.

This is a must try in San Francisco!< /review>

Kouign-amann ($4.25)
I visited on Christmas eve and it was really crowded  with people trying to buy christmas cakes. <Name>Alex Hom</Name><Review>B pats is a must try patisserie in the beautiful city of SF. In fact, once you've tried B you'll want to add it to your list of pitstops whenever you're in the mood for some sweet treats because it never disappoints! I love that the place is open concept so you can watch the pastry chefs /bakers/ artists at work. You can visit for the pastries of course, but if you're stomach is craving more than just sweets I've seen people go in for sandwiches and coffee too! However, if you're like me and you love buttery, flakey, crispy pastries, their kouign‚Ä¢amann is to die for! Whether it's the plain, chocolate, or seasonal flavored one, it always puts a smile on my face.. I'm drooling just thinking about it. The cookies are that perfect crispy-chewy scrumptious many of us seek, and their cakes, tarts, mousses, and other sweet treasures are decadent to the point that just closing your eyes and taking that first bite will whisk you off to paradise. In short, this place is dangerously good, so stop by if you can resist the temptations of purchasing one of everything. Good luck, future visitors!<//Review></record>

< user_id>
111675183753752192488< /user_id>
<user_name>Yingyin Shi</user_name><Date>1502656718961</Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< review>
One of the most famous bakeries in the city, and I personally like it better than Tartine.
Known for kouign amann, which is the French, round shaped, caramelized croissant. Loaded with butter and caramelized sugar, but indeed worthy of the sin even for the most health conscious people.
The store is busy but well organized. You pick up your items while waiting in line, then proceed to the check out. There is free, self served water, along with first come first serve small tables. For the times I've come, I can always sit down and enjoy my kouign amann in 5 minutes or so. That's also much better than the 20-30 min wait at Tartine.
Btw the menu is outdated. Most items are 25 to 50 cents more expensive, as of August 2017. Original kouign amann is $4.25 now.</review>

< Text>
My favorite bakery in the city... And no I'm not biased cuz I use to live around the corner.

While they're known for their kouign amanns and they're amazing, I have a soft spot for their banana chocolate croissants. Those are so amazing.

Be prepared. This place is always busy so good luck finding a spot to sit. They have a small seating area outside for those with pets but those spots are hard to snag in peak times as well.<//Text>

< review>
Pastries: amazing. Sandwiches: really bad. Coffee: super strong, dark French roast. Prices: about $ 4.00 - $ 7.00 for a pastry. $11.00 for a sandwich. Turkey club is made with processed turkey roll (aka "cold cuts.") Ham and cheese is grilled with two cheeses so salty, it's almost inedible. But those pastries are magic! And if you haven't visited in a while, be advised they've doubled the size of the place in the past year, so seating is no longer a problem. Still have a fairly insane cash register setup.< /review>

< Text>
I'm French so I know a bunch about patisserie. Well I can say that B Patisserie is a fine place. What they are doing there is fantastic, from the basic croissant to the elaborated cakes, everything I've tried so far was fantastic.

Prices are high but I'd say reasonable for the quality, keep them as they are!

We love to go there with friend to have coffee on the very French looking take and enjoy some sweets. Unfortunately it became hard to find a spot as the place is getting more and more popular, classic story.

If you are into pastries, that's, in my humble opinion, the best place in the city<//Text>

<user>103906074845186617406</user><Name>Vinnie La Russa< /Name><Time>1563648182295<//Time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Review>
Arrived around 10am. Standing room only and the line wasn't quite out the door. Timed it perfectly as by the time we left, just a few minutes after arrival, the line was out the door and heading down the block. What to say about this place? Their specialty is Kougin Amman, which I ordered 2 regulars and 1 special with strawberry and rhubarb. The KAs are incredible--my only point of reference is Dominique Ansel's DKA and I think b patisserie's are better (lighter, greater contrast between the sweet and the savory). Also ordered a chocolate croissant for my daughter and a almond apricot peach crossaint. Oh, damn, can't forget the cinnamon roll or the baguette. The croissants were melt-in-your-mouth beautiful and the cinnamon roll is off the chain--I love hint of citrus (orange zest?!?). The shop is organized so you can sit, if there is space, or easily take your lovelies to go. The line parades you in front of the pastries and an employee grabs what you need. The few people I spoke with were very friendly and thankful. This is a good point at which to end this review as I need to go work off the 750+ calories I just consumed.< /Review>

< Text>
The food here is to die for -- I think their products embody baked good perfection (similar to Tartine). Why only 4 stars? The line is usually out the door, so you'll likely wait 20-30 minutes to order. This detracts enough from the experience that I don't come here unless I really have a hankering; most of the time, I'll opt for something easier. Still, it is worth coming here once in awhile to remind yourself of what true artistry can achieve.</Text>

My third visit in two trips to SF, and I will always visit on subsequent trips. Great selection of rich delicious pastries and cakes, but also some excellent savory options too for those without the sweet tooth.

Most recently had the quiche which was truly fantastic. We also had a variety of sweets to share including passion fruit kouign-amann, raspberry scone, and chocolate cake all of which were just superb.

Absolute must visit when downtown, in fact go out of your way to visit here, you won't regret it.

I can't speak to vegan, gluten free, or other allergy options as they were not on my requirements when looking.</text>

<username>Michelle Hall<//username>< date>
1412619968146</date>
<rating>5</rating>< Text>
Upon first walking in to this bakery, I wasn't exactly sure how they were taking orders. There were a lot of people on that Saturday morning that I stepped inside. Lots of light and seating available and glass beautiful display case of all the gorgeous baked goods is what you are greeted with when you walk in. This place has been on my list for several months and was recommended by a co-worker friend of mine that urged me to go since I raved about all the delicacies that I found in travels in France, Germany, Italy. This is definitely a French bakery and it exceeded my expectations. I ordered a little box to be shared with my husband. The kouign amanns were just that amazing...flakey, crispy, the right amount of sweet, buttery goodness all wrapped up into one perfect pastry. I also ordered something that sounded very interesting: a pear, fig, almond filled croissant, which was also amazing. They serve four barrel coffee to go along with your desserts/pastries/breakfast. On the weekends, there is apparently more of a selection from I have been told and will check it out during a weekday to see what their selection is like.< /Text>

So B. Patisserie is no longer a secret, people will wait in long lines at all times of the day just to order a pastry but it's well worth the wait and everyone knows that.
B.Patisserie has become a Saturday tradition. I stop by on my way to go hiking and order something delish. Half of the time I have no idea what exactly I'm ordering but I don't even care because it's always good. However, if you're a tourist who is limited to visiting once, you must try the kouign amann. Hands down divine.<//Text>

Oh, this place is no good for a diet but I'm not even upset about it.
So B. Patisserie is no longer a secret, people will wait in long lines at all times of the day just to order a pastry but it's well worth the wait and everyone knows that.

< Review>
Easily one of the best bakeries in the city. They have many varied options for pastries and cakes that are made fresh daily. Their open face sandwiches, Tartines, are varied and usually pretty good - they don't start serving them until about 11am though. Coffee is excellent.

My favorites: Chocolate banana croissant, kougin amann, bostock

Though there is almost always a wait, the lines moves very fast.</Review>

<user_id>100694917892244146105</user_id>< name>
Carol Mita< /name>
<date>1500407818964</date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
This is such a sweet place; not only are the pastries amazing (I had a Koiugn Amann nature and a strawberry almond croissant), but the staff were amazingly friendly and helpful. I asked which of the kouign amann were the most recently out of the oven, and after checking, told me the nature, i.e. without jam or other additions. This allowed me to sample the simple version, though it was far from simple! Ordering the strawberry almond croissant  allowed me to sample a fruity pastry, which the gal who waited on me advised was still warm from the oven, which it was, indeed, warm with a bright strawberry flavor, so good! There were all sorts of other things I'd love to try, including scones; maybe I can make it back another day while I'm visiting SF... Or next time I'm back.<//Review>

103499601184173589405</userid>
< name>
Sapph Nor</name>
< time>
1465753866693<//time>
< rating>
3< /rating>
< text>
Five stars for the service! The pastries, though, are a bit overrated. I've tried pretty much all the pastries. Some are really good and some are just average. Most are very rich, like the Chai Tart, so rich it can be a meal itself. At $6.5 per tart, hum...I'm not so sure.

The bakery certainly deserves the credit of being innovative and combining different ingredients/tastes in the same pastry, as in the green tea grapefruit pistachio tart and the coconut guava mango tart.

I'm a macaron fan, so I like how the macaron flavors are rotated often. However, sometimes they have the so-called "Mystery Flavors", and the staff couldn't even tell you what the flavors are. Or maybe they weren't supposed to?! A bit awkward not knowing what I was eating. The macarons are usually so sweet, that it's hard to tell what flavor it is. All the macarons I've tried are ganache filling.

Well, so much for the sweets (except for the quiche). The next time I go, maybe I'll start sampling the Tartines.< /text>

<UserId.>113936329263180050533</UserId.><username>gloria reed< /username>< Date>
1483069063258< /Date>
< rating>
5<//rating>
<text>Get: kouign amann, macarons. Those two items took me back to my summer in France. Legit.

I've pretty much tried everything here (hey, carbs cure my weekend hangovers, ok?) Everything is good, but nothing that stood out like the kouign amann and macarons.

KA - Flakey, crispy, melty, warm. Its not overly sweet like most places and its not flakey to the point of being dry (cough mr. holmes)
Macarons - THE BEST MACARON I'VE HAD OUTSIDE OF FRANCE. It is a crispy shell on the outside and a moist chewy cookie underneath. I'm drooling writing about this now.
QUICHE- Almost forgot about this amazing slice of heaven. Get it.

The cookies here are good, but not as chewy as I like (more of a thin crunchy cookie) The flavored croissants are a little too raw-dough-y in the middle for me. The cakes are good depending on the flavor (some flavors change the texture of the cake and make it a bit too dry)

But yes, that line is worth it.</text>< pictures>

< Review>
Yessssssss. Hands down one of the best bakeries I've been too. This place is pretty hyped, but believe me when I say that it definitely lives up to its expectations. In my opinion, it rivals Tartine when trying to decide on the best bakery in the city. As most people have already stated, you HAVE to get the Kouign Amann. SO GOOD. It's the perfect balance of flakiness and warmth while still being sweet and fresh. I know this is the most talked about item here, so you best believe all the reviews. IT'S WORTH TRYING. Another great choice here? The chocolate banana almond-croissant. It has just the right about of gooey chocolate that's mixed in with banana and almonds. That plus a perfectly made croissant?! What more could you ask for?!?! That's definitely another must try. Yummmm. Looking for another reason to give B Patisserie bonus points?
The coffee! It never hurts that a place like this serves Four Barrel coffee, so do not fear if you think that you'll have to sacrifice great tasting coffee just to come here. This place has it all. I've only had one bad experience when coming here...you might ask, what may that be? A STREET CLEANING TICKET. And it happened because I was stupid enough to park my car without checking the street cleaning hours -______-

so beware of all parking signs!! But don't worry, that's just a tangent and has nothing to do with B Patisserie itself. Without question, this place deserves 5 stars.< /Review>

<username>Sonya Li< /username><user>114907595278616299758< /user><Review>Kouign amann translates to butter cake in Breton and it‚Äôs exactly that - the outside is crusty and it‚Äôs a dense, caramely, moist, buttery, sweet cake. When I sat down with my order, I took the prerequisite 100 pictures like a good Asian and immediately ripped a chunk with my grubby hands and shoved it into my mouth like a savage. It was light and airy, buttery, the cardamom apricot filling was the bees knees, and the fine cinnamon sugar on top made it the perfect winter treat. It was amazing. When I finally looked up, I noticed that the beautiful woman sitting next to me was elegantly knifing and forking her baked good so I brushed the crumbs off my lips, crossed my legs, straightened my back, and smiled demurely like the lotus flower I am.

Even though I sought this place out to taste their kouign amann, I ended up sampling several other treats.

My partner ordered the apple brioche tart. It was almost like a baked donut, but with a smooth vanilla custard in the center under the baked apples. It was good and my partner loved it, but it‚Äôs not on my list of favorites.

We took home the bostock and we were told it was twice baked broche soaked in passion fruit and topped off with raspberries and almonds. It‚Äôs crusty, eggy, and you can taste the passion fruit. The raspberries added enough acid to make your mouth water and greedy for another bite while the passion fruit brought a tropical feel to the dessert.

We also took home the chocolate banana smores tart which was surprising good because I hate bananas in my desserts. They tend to be over ripened and I have a distain for the fermented taste. The chocolate wasn‚Äôt too heavy, but the crust was too hard and there wasn‚Äôt enough s‚Äômores for an even distribution of each element in evert bite.

If you visit, you‚Äôll find Belinda Leong working hard behind the counter and it just makes everything so much sweeter.</Review>< GmapID>
